\begin_layout Standard
After finding out what everyone had experienced in the Sovereign Gate, Zach and
 Zorian departed from the Noveda Estate and went to ransack Silverlake's
 dimensional refuge for any clues.
 Of course, Zorian fully intended to also steal any magical secrets or notable
 resources he found there.
 Since Silverlake had betrayed them so utterly, he did not feel bad about
 robbing her blind in the slightest.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, it seemed that Silverlake's spite and paranoia knew no bounds.
 When they finally managed to subvert her defenses and break into her pocket
 dimension, they found it utterly wrecked.
 It had been reduced to a smoking crater for quite some time before they
 arrived, most likely because some dead man's switch had activated when she
 died and destroyed everything.
 Zorian left a couple of simulacrums to sift through the wreckage for anything
 of value, but he didn't have much hope they would find anything.
 The destruction was quite thorough.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only things that survived relatively intact was a curious arrangement of
 stones that was apparently responsible for powering her pocket dimension.
 He had long wondered how she was doing that, since the location itself could
 not support the dimensional magic she was using to isolate it from the rest of
 the world.
 Now he knew.
 Each of the heavy linking stones, which were build right into the walls of her
 hideout to disguise them better, had a matching counterpart in the deep in the
 underworld below her base.
 The underworld stones siphoned ambient mana from the Dungeon and sent it
 straight into Silverlake's hideout through the paired stones in the pocket
 dimension.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He supposed that if he ever wanted to destroy Silverlake's pocket dimension, he
 now knew a really easy way to do it.
 He just had to wreck the mana siphoning stones in the Dungeon below her
 sanctuary and the whole place would soon fall apart on its own.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, with this matter currently being dealt with, Zach and Zorian
 turned their attention towards the next thing that had to be done as soon as
 possible.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They had to go back to the Sovereign Gate and talk to the Guardian of the
 Threshold.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There was danger in doing that, of course.
 However, it had to be done.
 They had to confirm their suspicions.
 First, they had to see if the Guardian would still be there at all when they
 came back, since it had gone missing when they had last left the Sovereign
 Gate.
 Secondly, they had to see if the gate really was barred again like they
 suspected.
 If so, a lot of their speculation would be all but confirmed.
 

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, they had to see if the Guardian could shed some light on what happened
 during their last visit.
 While it had seemed like nothing more than an automated puppet in the past,
 there was clearly something more complex going on in regards to that thing.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only the two of them would be going there this time, of course.
 Considering Panaxeth completely ignored Zach the last time around and told
 Zorian he would not bother with him in the future, they probably wouldn't be
 seeing him on this visit.
 Even if they did, though, Zorian was far less afraid of him now that he knew
 he couldn't just reach into his head and start editing things.
 Whatever restrictions the primordial was laboring under, they clearly
 prevented him from coercing people into anything.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When they entered the Sovereign Gate, they were relieved to see the familiar
 figure of the Guardian of the Threshold floating in front of them.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Welcome, Controller," the Guardian greeted.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"So Panaxeth didn't break everything with his little visit," Zach commented,
 loudly exhaling in satisfaction.
 "That's great.
 Finally some good news."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes," Zorian agreed.
 He turned towards the floating humanoid of light, giving him a complex look.
 What was this thing really? "Guardian, is the gate still open?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They waited for several seconds, wondering why it took the Guardian so long to
 answer that.
 Usually he was really prompt with his answers, only occasionally waiting while
 it looked up something in the background.
 As the seconds ticked by, though, they realized he wasn't checking up on
 things before giving them an answer.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead, the Guardian ignored Zorian's question completely.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uh oh…

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Hey Guardian! Is the gate still open?" Zach said, repeating Zorian's question.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"No, Controller.
 The gate is barred," the Guardian immediately answered.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zach and Zorian shared a complex look with each other.
 On one hand, they just confirmed their speculation about what happened.
 This was good.
 It meant they were of the right track.
 On the other hand…

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Guardian, why did you answer his question and not mine?" Zorian asked the
 glowing humanoid.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the Guardian ignored his question, just like he did the previous one.
 In fact, Zorian realized that, although the Guardian was facing them, he was
 subtly tilted towards Zach.
 It was like he was completely ignoring Zorian's very existence.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just like he had been ignoring the temporary loopers in the past.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Guardian, why are you only responding to me and not him?" Zach asked, a bit of
 frustration bleeding into his voice.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I only respond to the Controller," the Guardian stated placidly.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I knew it," Zorian said quietly, followed by a small sigh.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zach stared at the Guardian, getting visibly more and more upset as time went
 by.
 Zorian just felt a sinking feeling of defeat, instead.
 When it rained, it poured.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"This is bullshit," Zach stated angrily, pointing with his finger at Zorian.
 "He entered this space on his own, by activating his marker.
 Only a controller can do that!"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes," the Guardian agreed.
 "He is an anomaly.
 Those happen sometimes.
 Something or someone has managed to get past the safeguards and disrupted the
 integrity of the mechanism.
 The anomaly can access Controller privileges even though he is not one.
 I am unable to do anything about that at the moment, but do not worry – the
 mistake will be corrected at the end of this cycle, when the world is
 recreated again."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lovely.
 Zorian did not need a detailed explanation to understand what the Guardian was
 implying.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"But why now?" Zach demanded.
 "How did you figure out he was the anomaly all of a sudden? He had been coming
 and going here for ages now!"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes.
 Regretful," Guardian said blandly.
 "However, you have presented me with the Key recently, which triggered a
 complete analysis of the existing situation.
 During this inspection, the anomaly was identified and correction procedures
 were scheduled to be performed at the first possible opportunity."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Why?" Zach asked.
 "What is it about the Key that triggers this?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Activating the Key signifies that something has gone wrong with the time loop
 mechanism," The Guardian answered, as if that was the most obvious thing in
 the world.
 "Of course a thorough check of everything is in order."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"It does? You never mentioned this when we asked you about the Key," Zach
 stated accusingly.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Guardian ignored the statement.
 Zorian was actually a little taken aback by this, since it meant the Guardian
 had probably kept them deliberately in the dark about that when they had
 talked to him in the past.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He supposed it made sense.
 The key was a security measure meant to confirm the Controller's identity.
 It made sense not to discuss the details of its operation unless the Guardian
 felt he had to, for some reason.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"What about those privileges I claimed, then?" Zach asked.
 "What does that get me?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"It affirms your status as the one true Controller and locks out all the other
 pretenders that may be walking about," the Guardian said.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"What!?" Zach protested incredulously.
 "That's it? No new functions or abilities or anything like that?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"As a Controller, you already have all the privileges," the Guardian told him.
 "You have simply ensured others do not infringe on this."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Why can Zorian even access this place, then?" Zach demanded.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hey!

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"He is an anomaly," the Guardian said.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"These 'privileges' are such a rip-off," Zach complained.
 "It doesn't even do what it's supposed to properly.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I'm sorry," the Guardian said, sounding honestly apologetic.
 "He's a very frustrating anomaly."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'And thank the gods for that,' Zorian thought.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He wasn't panicking, strangely enough.
 He didn't know why.
 Maybe because he already faced a very dire situation today and was rather
 emotionally drained at the moment, but finding out he was going to be deleted
 at the end of the month only brought a dull mixture of dread and determination
 to his mind.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So what if Silverlake had betrayed them? So what if Panaxeth was actively
 working against him? So what if he would get erased at the end of the month?
 Hadn't they already planned to make an escape attempt in this restart?

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They just had to make sure it worked.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He looked over at Zach, who had stopped arguing with the Guardian and was
 instead looking at Zorian like he was a dead man.
 A mixture of horror and guilt was etched clearly into his face.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Don't beat yourself over this," Zorian told Zach.
 His voice was so calm and even that even he was surprised how confident he
 sounded.
 "There was nothing else we could have done.
 You heard what the Guardian said – the moment we presented the Key to him, I
 was marked for erasure.
 It was always a given that we would do that the moment we gathered all the
 pieces.
 We should be grateful it was so difficult and took us that long to do it, or
 else we would have ended up in this situation at a much earlier and far less
 favorable restart."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"But, Zorian!" Zach protested.
 "You, you…"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"This just means I need to get out of here before this month ends.
 It's the same situation the rest of the group is laboring under, really,"
 Zorian said.
 "Don't tell me you've already given up?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"N-No… no…" Zach said slowly, taking a few deep breaths.
 "Damn it.
 I really hate this."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Ask the Guardian if the Key still works.
 Can you unbar the gate again?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He could, it turned out.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Do you want to do it now?" the Guardian asked.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"No!" Zach shouted at it.
 "No.
 Do nothing until I tell you, you useless thing."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"As you wish," the Guardian said peacefully, completely oblivious to their
 emotional turmoil.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There was a few seconds of silence as neither Zach nor Zorian said anything.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Well…" said Zorian finally.
 "We should probably end this for now.
 We need to come here later to ask more questions, but I don't think either of
 us is in the right frame of mind to do so at the moment."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yeah, I guess," Zach gloomily agreed.
 "I just–"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suddenly, the Guardian started convulsing again.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Oh, not this shit again!" Zach protested in an exasperated tone.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zorian made no moves to exit the Sovereign Gate this time.
 He probably couldn't even if he wanted to, but this time he actually wanted to
 have a talk with Panaxeth, so he didn't even try.
 Interestingly, Panaxeth did not bother to separate Zach from Zorian this time
 around and simply possessed the convulsing Guardian in front of them both.
 The glowing humanoid erupted into a forest of blood-red branches and tentacles
 before shuddering and contracting into a more human-like mass.
 It then quickly shapeshifted into the same female form that it had chosen for
 Zorian the last time they spoke.
 It did so far quicker than last time, apparently having gotten more proficient
 with the process.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It took a step forward, seemingly intending to walk over to them, before
 pausing and stopping in place.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Hello Zorian," Panaxeth said in a pleasant female voice.
 "We meet again."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I thought you said you would not bother talking to me again," Zorian
 immediately pointed out.
 "That it was a one-time offer."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Bah, I told you it was just playing hard to get," Zach stated.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Getting past the safeguards on this mechanism is not an easy thing to do,"
 Panaxeth said.
 "It is not easy for me to appear before you like this.
 I meant what I said last time, but I decided you are more interesting than I
 first realized."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Last time you didn't even dare show your face in front of me," Zach said
 loudly in a challenging tone, folding his hands over his chest.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"As the Controller, you are especially well protected from any tampering,"
 Panaxeth said, shifting its attention towards Zach for a moment.
 "And you can leave at any time.
 You do not require my help, nor am I able to stop you from leaving.
 You are of no use to me."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"But here you are, showing yourself in front of me anyway," Zach pointed out.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I need to conserve my power," Panaxeth said.
 "Isolating you in a separate space is costly and unnecessary.
 I do not care if you hear us."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The female form Panaxeth was wearing turned its attention back to Zorian,
 staring at him intently.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"You still have a chance to survive this," Panaxeth said.
 "I have managed to stop the Guardian from rescinding all your Controller
 privileges.
 Wreck the Controller's mind as much as you're able, use the key to unbar the
 gate, and I will incarnate you in the outside world.
 I do not even ask that you make a contract with me.
 Grievously sabotaging the Controller and preventing him from exiting the time
 loop will be payment enough for your salvation."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zach actually floated a few steps back when he heard that.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"You don't want me as an agent?" Zorian asked, frowning.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I already have two of them.
 That's more than enough," Panaxeth said.
 "If I can ensure that the Controller dies here when the time loop collapses
 upon itself, it will be far more valuable to me than any additional number of
 agents."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neither Zach nor Zorian said anything for a few seconds, but Zorian was
 furiously thinking about things.
 If Panaxeth was so desperate to take Zach out of the picture… that probably
 meant this entire time loop had been made specifically to help him find a
 reliable way to stop Panaxeth's release.
 Even if Zach could not remember so, the two of them were mortal enemies.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Before I helped Zach gather all the pieces of the Key, you were already
 winning," Zorian realized.
 "You had already sent one of the temporary loopers out as your agent, and Zach
 had mostly forgotten his mission to stop you.
 He only had vague feelings to guide him in what he must do.
 Even if he figured out how to come here, the gate was barred and he couldn't
 leave."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes.
 It would have been better for me if the Key had never been found," Panaxeth
 admitted readily.
 "However, I am the very embodiment of adaptability.
 I do not blame you for looking out for your best interests.
 I simply recruited one of you as my agent, thinking that was the best way to
 make use of the situation.
 It was only later that I found out how capable you are at mind invasion, and
 how the original plan could still be salvaged."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"You didn't know that before?" Zorian asked.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I'm always watching," Panaxeth said.
 "Everything, everywhere.
 But my consciousness is a lot like yours, in that I can't pay attention to
 every little detail I see.
 When you observe an anthill, you perceive a lot, but can you really remember
 what one particular ant does at any point of time? But I remember it all with
 perfect clarity, and I can review it all later as I wish.
 Just like 

\emph on

you

\emph default

 can remember things with perfect clarity when you want to.
 See? We're a lot more alike than you might think, Zorian."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The female shape Panaxeth was using as his avatar smiled.
 It was a bright, sunny smile that was probably meant to put him at ease but
 which Zorian found inexplicably terrifying.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"We're both trapped in this cage, doing anything we can, even distasteful
 things, in order to get out," Panaxeth continued.
 "Do you think I want to destroy your city? Its destruction is simply an
 unfortunate consequence of being in the wrong place at the wrong time.
 I never asked your kind to build a city around me.
 Just like you are willing to kill your outside self to live, I am willing to
 obliterate everything around me to get free.
 It is not my fault my fatality count is higher than yours."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I will die if I don't get out of here in time," Zorian pointed out.
 "You won't."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"The cage that binds me is torture you can barely imagine," Panaxeth countered.
